title: For Sale/Trade:  Rare Egyptian Rasheed
postcontent:
For sale is an original Egyptian Rasheed (Rashid) semi-automatic carbine in 7.62x39mm.  Built for the Egyptian military the Rasheed was based off of the design of the Swedish Ljungman and Egyptian Hakim rifles.  Less than 8000 of these rifles were ever made and out of those produced only about 2000 were imported in to the united states, making this a very rare and collectible military surplus rifle. 

  The Rasheed I am selling here was produced in 1968 and is in better condition than most of the ones I have seen pictures of on the internet.  The gun has all it's original parts with the same four digit serial number written on the bolt, bolt carrier, receiver and butt plate.  The stock has never been removed and still has the locking wires in place on the three receiver screws.  There is a working adjustable regulator for the guns direct impingement gas system, and a detachable 10 round box magazine that can be loaded using SKS stripper clips.  A folding blade bayonet is attached to the underside of the barrel, and a sun bleached sling that is correct for this rifle is also included.  

  These guns don't come up for sale very often and when they do they usually sell for $800 or more.  I would like to keep this gun in the state so I would prefer a face to face sale with a local Vermont resident only.

title: For Sale:  Remington Nylon 66
postcontent:
I have for sale a Nylon 66. I have bought and sold any number of these rifles over the years and this is one of the nicer ones I've had. Nylon 66's in good shape are getting harder and harder to find! This one is in solid shape, and yet it shows just enough honest use that you won't worry about shooting it. These are great guns, among my all time favorites. Bluing is in great shape, there is very minor freckling on the left side of the receiver, and a couple minor marks on the right below the ejection port. Stock is excellent, no cracks or chips. There is one small ding on the left of the buttstock, and one on the right. There are a few more significant scratches on the underside near the bedding screw, please see pictures, they tell the story better than I can.Barrel is excellent, bore is bright, and I have fired 100 rounds through this gun to test it and it ran flawlessly. Nylons usually do. This gun is very light, just 4.16 pounds, and very quick and handy. I have owned and shot Nylon 66's for over 40 years and am obviously a big fan of them. Woods rifle, trapping gun, truck gun, boat gun, whatever, the Nylon 66 is a great .22. 
Glad to provide additional pictures on request!

title: For Sale:  Very rare Naval contract Potsdam Model 1809 .75 Cal musket (percussion conversion)
postcontent:
Model 1809 .75 Cal Potsdam musket (percussion conversion), ultra rare Naval/Marine contract.  Thousands of Model 1809 Potsdam muskets were imported by the Union during the US Civil War.  Although they were converted from flintlocks to percussion in the 1830s and 1840s, they were still considered obsolete by the time of the US Civil War.  Despite their obsolescence, the Union still purchased thousands of them mainly to keep them from falling into the hands of confederate agents who were also trying to buy weapons in Europe, and because the price was right.  Many of these weapons were issued to militia units early in the war, and some found their way to Western theater battlefields where they were put to good use until the Northern industrial machine could catch up with weapons production for it's quickly growing armies.

The Naval contract gun is the rarest of the Potsdam 1809s and differs in several ways to the standard infantry model.  I've included the infantry model in some of the photos just for comparison sake, but it is not for sale.  As you can see in the photos, they use the exact same lock plate, butt plate, brass nose cap, and barrel (.75 cal x 41 & 3/16").  Overall length of the naval contract gun is about 1/2" longer than the infantry model with all the extra length in the butt.  Naval contract gun also differs in the following ways, starting from muzzle to butt.

1.  No bayonet lug nor evidence that it ever had one.  In early 19th century military thinking, the bayonet was to defend against cavalry, not ship to ship fighting.  
2.  Steel ramrod replaced by wood ram rod.  Wood was lighter and is one less thing that will rust in the salt sea air.
3.  Fore end of the stock shortened by about 2 inches bringing the brass nose cap/band back about farther from the muzzle. 
4.  Omission of the 2nd and 3rd barrel band.  These weren't removed from the gun, they were just never installed in the first place.  So the stock has a smooth taper instead of abrupt step downs where the infantry model would at the bands.  Also since the bands were never installed, there are no insets for the barrel band springs.
5.  Use of blackened brass tubes under the stock to keep the ramrod in place since there were no barrel bands.
6.  No sling swivels.  Since it did not have the second barrel band, there was no forward sling swivel.  The trigger guard has the hole for the rear swivel because this was a standard cast brass piece, but no evidence that the swivel itself was ever installed.
7.  Omission of the cheek cut out on the left side of the butt stock normally seen on the infantry model.
8. Shellacked stock from end to end, to better seal and protect the wood from the ocean environment.
9.  Blackened barrel.  I'm not sure exactly what they used but appears to be a semi glossy black type of paint.  It is scratched but retains about 90-95%.  I have done nothing to restore it.  This is exactly as I found it.

The action works as it should with good strong spring, and trigger pull.  Half cock (safety position) also works as it should, not allowing the hammer to fall when the trigger is pulled.  Nipple is in good condition and I actually have test fired this gun with powder only, not with actual ball ammo.  I fired it a total of three times with a charge of 60 grains of powder and paper wadding each time.  It functioned flawlessly with a good little pop each time, and I did give it a gentle but thorough cleaning after the test shots.  I've been shooting black powder for about 20 years, so I know the importance of cleaning a musket and how to do it properly.

As often seen with many of these old Model 1809s, this one has had some damage to the stock just above the rear of the lock plate.  Fortunately they saved the piece of broken off wood, and glued it back into place.  Because of this damage, I have not tried to remove the barrel, so I cannot tell you the exact date when it was converted to percussion which should be stamped on the underside of the barrel.  If you want to give it a try after you buy it, feel free, but I did not want to risk damaging it to find out.  

There is also a small chip out of the wood just at the front edge of the lock, but this piece is long gone, and is NOT a fresh chip so this happened probably when the musket was in service.  Other than that, there is no other major or even minor damage beyond the normal small handling dings on the stock, some light surface rust pitting on the butt plate, and tarnished brass.

Makers mark on the plate is Neisse.  Yes it looks like Neifse, but that is just the styling of the font.  So this musket, or at least the lock plate, was manufactured at the arsenal in the town of Neisse which at the time was in Germany (or Prussia), but due to the shifting borders of Europe over the past 200 years, is now located in current day Czech Republic.

Well enough history lesson.  I've taken several photos, but I'm limited to posting 3 here so e-mail if you need to see more, or if you have any questions.
